Medical\/Surgical History: had a long histoy of diabetes mellitus

Laboratory Values: her haemoglobin was 7.2 g/dl; platelets 62.000/ml; microangiopathic haemolysis together with impaired hepatic (serum lactate dehydrogenase 1260 iu/l (range 135–225); total bilirubin 1.4 mg/dl (range 0–1.1); serum aspartate aminotransfer-ase 870 iu/l (range 5–40); serum alanine aminotransferase 772 iu/l (range 5–40)) and renal function tests (3.5 g protein in a 24-h urine specimen; serum bun 36 mg/dl (range 4.7–23); creatine 1.1 mg/dl (range 0.6–1.2) and uric acid 7.1 mg/dl (range 55.7) the normal range for uric acid was 0.1–5.7

Family History: no known significant family history
Medical\/Surgical History: abdominal distention and bilateral pedal oedema for last 10 years; treated for right sided heart failure several times in the past, and one of these admissions prompted referral to a cardiac specialist; he denied having paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea, orthopnoea or wheezing; no history of chest pain, palpitation or syncope
Signs and Symptoms: chronic right sided heart failure; classical features of left ventricular endomyocardial fibrosis with a prominent right ventricular apical aneurysm; thin-walled, apical aneurysm of right ventricle with multiple septations and marked obliteration of left ventricular apex; hypersignal in the subendocardium, consistent with the right ventricular involvement of endomyocardial fibrosis; classical features of left ventricular endomyocardial fibrosis, while on the right side the typical features were missing; grossly distended abdomen and bilateral pitting pedal oedema; pulse rate was 70/min, irregular and blood pressure was 130/80 mm hg; oxygen saturation level was 94% on room air; jugular venous pressure was markedly elevated up to the level of ear lobes with a prominent ‘y descent’; normal heart sounds with a systolic murmur of tricuspid regurgitation; shifting dullness and hepatomegaly; other systemic examinations were normal as is the remainder of physical examination; the 12-lead electrocardiogram showed intermittent atrial fibrillation; chest radiography revealed cardiomegaly due to significant right atrial enlargement; echocardiogram revealed grossly dilated right atrium, reduced right ventricular volume with a prominent apical aneurysm; restrictive flow pattern at both atrioventricular-valves and severe tricuspid regurgitation were noted; left ventricular apex was obliterated with calcification; there was significant pericardial effusion; endocardial calcification was detected during coronary angiography; ventriculography confirmed right ventricular aneurysm with dilated right ventricular outflow tract and obliteration of left ventricular apex; pressure tracings of right atrium showed classical ‘c-v waves’ with prominent ‘y descent’; pulmonary artery systolic pressure was 28mm hg; pullback tracings from rv aneurysm to rv cavity proper showed a pressure gradient of 15mm hg; the cardiovascular magnetic resonance imaging (cmr) study demonstrated the obliteration and aneurysm of left and right ventricle respectively; dilated right atrium and systemic venous congestion were noted; delayed enhanced phase showed high signal intensity in the right ventricular subendocardium; cardiac catheterisation demonstrated the characteristic right atrial ‘c-v waves’ with ‘y descent’ of restrictive physiology and ventriculography disclosed unique rv apical aneurysm
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: cardiovascular examination; 2d echocardiography; right ventriculography; cardiac magnetic resonance images; a delayed-enhancement sequence after the infusion of contrast; 12-lead electrocardiogram; chest radiography; echocardiogram; coronary angiography; pressure tracings; pullback tracings; cardiovascular magnetic resonance imaging (cmr); cardiac catheterisation
Diagnosis: emf with classical features of left ventricular involvement, but with right ventricular (rv) apical aneurysm which mimics arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy (arvc); biventricular endomyocardial fibrosis with right ventricular apical aneurysm
Laboratory Values: a full blood count, routine biochemical screen and serum bicarbonate levels were normal. absolute eosinophil count was with in normal range
Pharmacological Therapy: treated with diuretics and anticoagulation
Short Diagnosis: biventricular endomyocardial fibrosis; arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy

Family History: underwent ppi with an epicardial pacing lead on the right ventricle (rv) (fig; 2b) at the age of 30 years for symptomatic chb

Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: the echocardiographic examination showed dilated cardiac chambers with concentric left ventricular hypertrophy and left ventricular ejection fraction (lvef) of 27% (fig; 1a)
Diagnosis: complete heart block
Pharmacological Therapy: diuretics, digoxin, enalapril, amiodarone and oral anticoagulants
Interventional Therapy: pacemaker implantation; cardiac resynchronisation therapy (crt) implantation
Patient Outcome Assessment: after 12 weeks of follow-up, the patient has maintained the same nyha functional class (ii); the lvef was estimated by echocardiography to be 40% at 12 weeks of follow-up

Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: electrocardiogram showed an uncorrected qt interval exceeding 600 ms, with broad, biphasic, and deeply inverted t waves in multiple leads; invasive electrophysiological investigation, extensive endocardial catheter mapping
Diagnosis: congenitally deaf; ventricular fibrillation; jervell and lange-nielsen syndrome

Life Style: a history of heavy smoking and alcohol use and denied intravenous drug use or any recent dental procedures
Family History: family history was negative for thromboembolism or connective tissue disease
Medical\/Surgical History: a history of popliteal deep vein thrombosis 5 months earlier, for which was being anticoagulated with warfarin (5 mg daily)
Signs and Symptoms: 5-month history of weight loss, subjective fevers, chills, malaise, and a rash on the anterior aspect of both legs; significant physical findings included a temperature of 103°f, an apical holosystolic murmur radiating to the axilla, a diastolic decrescendo murmur in the aortic area, and 3+ bilateral lower extremity edema; there was a purpuric rash on the anterior aspect of his legs; his neurologic exam was nonfocal and his abdominal exam was benign; he complained of left upper quadrant pain
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: a repeat duplex scan of the lower extremities revealed recanalization of his popliteal vein; chest radiograph revealed blunting of the left costophrenic angle; a two-dimensional echocardiogram revealed vegetation on the aortic valve; contrast-enhanced computed tomography: splenic infarctions and a splenic collection demonstrated
Diagnosis: subacute bacterial endocarditis (sbe), splenic infarction, splenic abscess
Laboratory Values: initial laboratory data revealed a white blood cell count of 6.0×103/mm3, with 72.1% neutrophils, 16% lymphocytes, 10.3% monocytes, and 0.8% eosinophils. his hemoglobin was 9.3 g/dl and his platelet count was 158×103/mm3. his biochemistry panel revealed a normal serum creatinine (1.1 mg/dl), total protein of 6.8 mg/dl, and albumin of 2.6 mg/dl. his prothrombin time international normalized ratio was 4.7 c3 level was 33.8 mg/dl (normal: 79–152) and c4 was 11.7 mg/dl (normal: 16–38). ch50 was 16 u/ml (normal: 26–58 u/ml). rheumatoid factor was positive at a high titer (>1:320, normal <20). he had a strongly positive c-anca test at a titer of 34 u/ml (normal <2). urinalysis revealed 3–5 white blood cells/high-power field, hematuria (35–40 red blood cells/high-power field) and proteinuria. erythrocyte sedimentation rate was 115 mm/h. the patient’s blood, aortic valve, and splenic aspirate cultures were positive for ampicillin-sensitive enterococcus faecalis. a follow-up anca test was negative. sixteen months later, the patient demonstrated no evidence of systemic vasculitis
Pharmacological Therapy: warfarin (5 mg daily), ampicillin, gentamicin
Interventional Therapy: prosthetic aortic valve replacement, splenic collection was drained percutaneously; splenectomy
Patient Outcome Assessment: sixteen months later, the patient demonstrated no evidence of systemic vasculitis
Short Diagnosis: subacute bacterial endocarditis (sbe); splenic infarction; splenic abscess

Medical\/Surgical History: his gestational and birth history was unremarkable; he walked at 14 months of age; was noted to be motorically delayed at 2 years of age and developed a waddling gait by 3.5 years of age; when was 5 years old, was seen by a pediatric neurologist and was described as lordotic, with calf and tongue psuedohypertrophy, scapular winging, proximal greater than distal weakness in all extremities, and a gower's sign; his creatine kinase level was reported to be greater than 2000 u/l; his mother's creatine kinase level was elevated at 114 u/l, and his sister's creatine kinase level was 113 u/l (normal, 5 to 30 u/l); at 10 years of age, the patient was wheelchair bound, with advanced joint contractures and a thoracolumbar kyphoscoliosis; there was less than antigravity strength in most proximal muscles and neck flexors, as well as calf and tongue enlargement; the cardiac point of maximal impulse was not displaced, and a grade 2 (of6) soft ejection systolic murmur was heard at the left lower sternal border; an electrocardiogram was consistent with duchenne muscular dystrophy, with tall right precordial r waves (r/s ratio in v, equal to 1.4) and deep q waves in v3 and v6; the cardiac silhouette was normal on the chest roentgenogram; slow progression of his weakness over the next several years
Signs and Symptoms: six weeks before his admission on this occasion he had noticed aching pain in the left side of his chest radiating to the right shoulder; the pain was persistent and disturbed his sleep; he became increasingly breathless on exertion; he had a paroxysmal cough, bouts of which made him feel faint; because of these symptoms he was seen at the chest clinic, from whence he was admitted to sully hospital in june i962
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: examination (the patient had the typical pigmentation, pingueculae, hepatosplenomegaly, and other stigmata of gaucher's disease; the jugular venous pulse was raised, the pulse wave was paradoxical in type; cardiac dullness was increased and there was a protodiastolic triple rhythm on auscultation.); chest x-ray (showed gross cardiomegaly, suggesting pericardial effusion, and a small tuberculoma in the apical segment of the right upper lobe); electrocardiogram (suggested pericarditis); cardiac catheterization (confirmed a large pericardial effusion)
Diagnosis: haemorrhagic pericardial effusion likely due to thrombocytopenia due to hypersplenism from gaucher's disease
Laboratory Values: haematology showed a moderate pancytopenia: platelet count less than ioo,ooo/cu.mm. on numerous occasions. coagulation studies showed the only abnormality to be a reduced platelet count. serum acid phosphatase, 8 units (normal i-3 units). liver function tests normal. viral agglutination titres were raised for influenza a and psittacosis suggesting previous infections. faecal occult blood was occasionally positive. culture of gastric juice showed no acid-fast bacilli on i4 occasions. from the pericardial effusion, the haemoglobin concentration of the first sample of fluid was 4-45 g./ioo ml. at subsequent aspirations the haemoglobin concentration became progressively lower. no organisms, including acid-fast bacilli, were cultured from the fluid, and no abnormal cells were identified, normal blood cells only being found
Interventional Therapy: aspiration of the pericardial effusion was carried out on several occasions, the total amount of fluid aspirated being 2.75 litres; the fluid aspirated was heavily blood stained though not with fresh blood and was not coagulating
Patient Outcome Assessment: immediate symptomatic relief occurred after aspiration of the pericardial effusion; the signs of cardiac tamponade disappeared and the heart size and shape returned to normal; when investigations were completed the patient was discharged well; he has since been followed up as an outpatient and has shown no clinical or radiological evidence of further pericardial disease
Short Diagnosis: haemorrhagic pericardial effusion; thrombocytopenia; hypersplenism; gaucher's disease

Life Style: did not add salt to his meals but dined out regularly at italian restaurants
Medical\/Surgical History: there was no history of maternal lupus
Signs and Symptoms: his blood pressure remained elevated with his systolic pressure between 185 and 210 mm hg and his diastolic pressure between 90 and 100 mm hg; on examination, with the patient seated, his blood pressure was 210/92 mm hg and his heart rate was 58 beats/min; with the patient standing, his blood pressure was 202/91 mm hg and his heart rate was 54 beats/min; his pulses were equal in all extremities, and he had no ascites or jugular venous distention; mild nonpitting edema was present in his ankles bilaterally
Comorbidities: stage iii chronic kidney disease and dyslipidemia
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: a conventional renal angiogram in 2006 showed no evidence of renal artery stenosis; a computed tomographic scan of his abdomen revealed adrenal nodules of 8 mm to 10 mm in diameter bilaterally without evidence of malignancy; however, subsequent adrenal vein sampling showed lateralization of aldosterone production to the right adrenal gland
Diagnosis: resistent hypertension, primary aldosteronism, stage iii chronic kidney disease and dyslipidemia
Laboratory Values: his serum potassium was 3.5 meq/l; estimated glomerular filtration rate was 48 ml/min per 1.73 m2 (normal, >90 ml/min per 1.73 m2). his serum aldosterone level was markedly elevated at 52 ng/dl (normal <16 ng/dl; to convert to pmol/l, multiply by 27.75) and his plasma renin activity was suppressed below the minimal detectable limit of 1 ng/ml per hour (normal, 2.9-10.8 ng/ml per hour). the patient underwent an intravenous saline suppression test, which showed a persistently elevated serum aldosterone of 26 ng/dl despite the salt load
Pharmacological Therapy: aliskiren, amlodipine combination of valsartan, 160 mg daily; eplerenone, 50 mg twice daily; carvedilol, 25 mg twice daily; hydralazine, 100 mg 3 times a day; clonidine, 0.1 mg twice daily; and bumetanide, 1 mg daily
Interventional Therapy: right adrenalectomy
Patient Outcome Assessment: after surgery, he required only 2 medications to keep his blood pressure lower than 140/90 mm hg
Short Diagnosis: resistent hypertension; primary aldosteronism; dyslipidemia; stage iii chronic kidney disease

Life Style: the patient was a current smoker (10 pack-years)
Medical\/Surgical History: had a fairly unremarkable medical history; had two healthy children; she used no oral contraceptives or illicit drugs; there was no history of hypertension
Signs and Symptoms: a one hour history of chest pain; precordial discomfort started during housekeeping; on examination, her supine heart rate was 86 beats/min and blood pressure was 112/78 mm hg; she had no clinical signs of marfan’s syndrome or heart failure; chest pain at rest recurred 48 hours
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: on admission to hospital, her ecg showed st segment elevation in the precordial leads indicating acute anterior wall myocardial infarction; echocardiography showed a region of akinesia confined to the anterior wall and the apex of the left ventricle; the left ventricular lateral wall showed hypokinesia; the chest radiograph was normal; at coronary angiography she was found to have dissection of the left main stem, no stenotic lesions, and timi (thrombolysis in myocardial infarction) flow grade 3; left ventriculography showed moderately depressed left ventricular function and akinesia confined to the anterior and apical walls of the left ventricle; twenty four hours later, repeated echocardiography showed only a limited region of hypokinesia confined to the left ventricular apex; ecg again showed st segment elevation in the precordial leads indicating transmural acute anterior wall ischaemia; coronary angiography was repeated and showed disease progression and extension of the dissection to both the left anterior descending and the left circumflex arteries with subtotal occlusion and timi flow grade 1 of the first diagonal branch; intravascular ultrasound showed dissection and intramural haematoma starting from the left coronary ostium and progressing into the left anterior descending and the circumflex arteries; intramural haematoma in the media of the arterial wall resulted in compression of the real lumen and myocardial ischaemia; an intimal tear was not observed
Diagnosis: acute coronary syndrome; spontaneous coronary artery dissection
Laboratory Values: cardiac enzymes were slightly increased (creatine kinase (ck)) 204 u/l, normal range < 145 u/l; ck-mb fraction 23 u/l; troponin t 0.09 ng/ml, normal range < 0.03 ng/ml). ck values were increased with a peak concentration of 638 u/l (mb fraction 96 u/l)
Pharmacological Therapy: aspirin, enoxaparin, metoprolol, nitrates, opiates, clopidogrel, tirofiban
Interventional Therapy: emergency coronary artery bypass grafting (left internal mammary artery graft to the left anterior descending and vein grafts to the diagonal and circumflex arteries)
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient made an uneventful recovery
Short Diagnosis: Acute coronary syndrome; spontaneous coronary artery dissection

Medical\/Surgical History: her clinical history included polio-myelitis in her childhood resulting in right leg weakness; back surgery at the age of 12 for spina bifida; occasional urinary incontinence with recurrent urinary tract infections since the surgery; multinodular goiter; monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance for 20 years

Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: electrocardiography revealed small complexes; echocardiography dem- onstrated le ventricular hypertrophy with diastolic dysfunction; soon a er admission the patient underwent a fat-pad biopsy that was negative for amyloid by congo- red stain; gastroscopy was scheduled for 2 weeks; gastroscopy revealed erosive gastritis and duodenitis, and gastric biopsies were also sent for amy- loid; bone marrow biopsy was performed
Diagnosis: amyloid heart: heart failure with preserved ejection fraction--a rare cause of a common illness
Laboratory Values: laboratory test revealed creatinine 0.71 mg/dl (0.5–0.9 mg/dl), albumin 30 mg/dl (34–48 mg/dl), protein 80 mg/dl (64–83 mg/dl). electrolytes and liver function tests were normal; a thorough ambulatory investigation revealed anemia with hemoglobin 10 g/dl (11.7–15.7 g/dl) and erythrocyte sedimen- tation rate 84. yroid ultrasound demon- strated a multinodular goiter; chest x-ray and abdominal ultrasound were normal. electrophoresis of her urine showed 2.8 g of immunoglobulin g lambda protein, which correlated well with previous and recurrent studies over the last 20 years since mgus was rst described
Pharmacological Therapy: glucocorticoids/administration & dosage*
Interventional Therapy: intermediate care chest unit with a diagnosis of amyloid heart
Patient Outcome Assessment: a er stabilization she was referred to a tertiary hospital for completion of therapy where she is currently being treated

Medical\/Surgical History: underwent coronary artery bypass grafting in february 2000; he also developed ankle oedema in october 2002
Signs and Symptoms: progressive retrosternal chest pain, exertional dyspnea, tachycardia, and bilateral leg edema, persisting for 4 weeks
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: her ecg showed normal sinus rhythm, rightward axis, and intraventricular conduction delay; chest x-ray revealed mediastinal enlargement with mild cardiomegaly, pericardial calcification, and right pleural effusion; two-dimensional echocardiography demonstrated enhanced echogenicity of the pericardium suggesting the presence of calcification, biatrial enlargement, normal left ventricular dimensions, and systolic function (ejection fraction 59%), and abnormal ventricular septal motion; cardiovascular magnetic resonance imaging confirmed pericardial thickening with calcification, presence of constrictive physiology with septal bounce, and abrupt cessation of left ventricle diastolic filling; cardiac catheterization revealed equalization of end-diastolic pressures, and interdependence of ventricular pressures consistent with constrictive physiology; coronary angiogram demonstrated the obliteration of the second obtuse marginal branch of left circumflex artery in systole and diastole, and compression of the first obtuse marginal branch that induced mid to late diastolic interruption of coronary flow (
Diagnosis: segmental diastolic compression of circumflex coronary artery secondary to pericardial constriction: an uncommon cause of angina pectoris
Laboratory Values: liver function tests, electrolyte levels, cardiac enzymes, coagulation parameters, and urinalysis were within normal limits
Pathology: histopathologic examination of the pericardium excluded mycobacterium tuberculosis or granulomatous diseases
Interventional Therapy: the patient was referred to surgery and pericardiectomy was performed
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient was discharged home following surgery and her symptoms were improved during the postoperative follow-up
Short Diagnosis: segmental diastolic compression of circumflex coronary artery; pericardial constriction; angina pectoris

Medical\/Surgical History: she was a diabetic and hypertensive on therapy; in 2001, the patient had inferior wall myocardial ischemia with left ventricular dysfunction after which she underwent percutaneous transluminal coronary angioplasty with stent placement to the left circumflex (90% lesion) and the right coronary artery (95% lesion); she presented with severe back pain of 4-month duration
Signs and Symptoms: severe back pain of 4-month duration; 3 days after the 22nd dose (cumulative dose of bortezomib 28.6 mg/m2), the patient presented to the hospital emergency department with complaints of uneasiness and restlessness
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: skeletal survey (revealed compression collapse of d4-d6, d11, l1 and l5 vertebrae; old fractures were seen in the right inferior ischiopubic ramus and anterior pillar of the right acetabulum; lytic lesions were also seen in the right ala of the sacrum and multiple ribs.); two dimensional echocardiography (showed left ventricular ejection fraction (lvef)—45–50%, with trace tricuspid regurgitation (tr) and posterior and inferior wall akinesia.); 3 days after the 22nd dose of bortezomib: physical examination (revealed a pulse rate—106/min, blood pressure—180/100 mmhg, raised jugular venous pressure (jvp) and bilateral crepitations on chest examination); electrocardiogram (suggestive of sinus tachycardia); 2d echocardiography (revealed global hypokinesia with a left ventricular ejection fraction (lvef) of 25% with akinesia of the posterior and inferior wall); coronary angiography (revealed non-critical coronary artery disease with patent right coronary artery and left circumflex stents); 2d echocardiography performed after 96 hours of admission (revealed a lvef of 30–35%); 2d echocardiography 3 weeks later (revealed that the lvef was 40%)
Diagnosis: multiple myeloma, stage iii a and bortezomib-induced congestive cardiac failure
Laboratory Values: she was found to be anemic. her hemogram was the following: hemoglobin (hb)—6.7 g/dl (12–15 g/dl), total leukocyte count—8.6 × 109/l (4,000–10,000 109/l), platelets—160 × 109/l (150–450 × 109/l). peripheral smear was unremarkable except for rouleaux formation. kidney function tests were normal with serum urea—23/mg dl (15–38 mg/dl), serum creatinine—0.5 mg/dl (0.6–1.3 mg/dl), and liver function tests were also normal. serum protein electrophoresis was performed. m spike was present—4.94 g/dl. serum immunoelectrophoresis revealed the following: immunoglobulin a (iga)—49 mg/dl, immunoglobulin g (igg)—4,912 mg/dl, immunoglobulin m (igm)—<25 mg/dl. beta-2 microglobulin levels were also raised—6.178 mg/l (0.7–3.4 mg/l). urine electrophoresis was negative. after four months of weekly bortezomib, serum igg levels had reduced to 3,513 mg/dl. 3 days after the 22nd dose of bortezomib, cardiac enzymes measurements at presentation revealed creatinine phosphokinase (cpk)—52.0 iu/l (normal range: 26–140 u/ml), creatinine kinase—mb (ck–mb)—21.0u/l normal range (0–24.0 u/l), troponin i (trop-i)—0.04 ng/ml(normal range: <0.04 ng/ml). n-terminal pro-brain natriuretic peptide (nt-probnp)—4,030 pg/ml was increased (normal range: < 125 pg/ml). serial measurements of cardiac enzymes taken over the next 2 days were non-contributory and were as follows: cpk—47 iu and 39 iu, cpk–mb—17 and 14 iu and troponin i (0.05 and 0.04 ng/ml), respectively
Pathology: bone marrow aspiration and biopsy performed for the evaluation of multiple myeloma revealed 35% plasma cells. myeloid to erythroid ratio was 4:1
Pharmacological Therapy: she was started on inj. bortezomib (1.3 mg/m2) + tab. dexamethasone 40 mg on a weekly basis. after a cumulative dose of bortezomib 28.6 mg/m2, she was treated medically with diuretics, nitroglycerine drip, and low molecular weight heparin
Interventional Therapy: she was given 2 units of blood transfusion
Patient Outcome Assessment: evaluation after 3 months revealed that the lvef had returned to pretreatment levels of 45–50% with persistent akinesia of the posterior and inferior wall; the n-terminal pro-brain netriuretic peptide (nt-probnp) levels that were initially raised 4,030 pg/ml (<125 pg/ml) declined to 2,280 pg/ml a week later and subsequently normalized over the next 2 weeks; the patient responded well to the treatment and was then discharged; bortezomib was discontinued, and she was started on oral melphalan and prednisolone which she continues to take till date

Medical\/Surgical History: immunoglobulin g multiple myeloma
Signs and Symptoms: pulmonary oedema
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: echocardiography and radiology showed left ventricular hypertrophy and mixed aortic valve disease
Diagnosis: pulmonary oedema; bacterial endocarditis
Laboratory Values: blood cultures were sterile, the erythrocyte sedimentation rate was 5 mm in first hour; sedimentation rate was 40 mm in first hour and the haemoglobin concentration had fallen 2 g to 11-5 g/dl; haematological investigation disclosed low grade haemolysis with c3 and igg coating of the red cells and peripheral destruction of platelets. a positive coombs test result raised the possibility of evans's syndrome. two sets of blood cultures were sterile; culture of blood before death and of vegetations grew an a haemolytic streptococcus of group g, probably streptococcus millern (streptococcal reference laboratory, colindale). the organism was tolerant of amoxycillin, having a minimal inhibitory concentration of 0-025 mg/l and a minimal bactericidal concentration of > 10 mg'l
Pathology: necropsy showed a large heart (750 g) with severe dilatation and hypertrophy of the left ventricle. the aortic valve comprised three cusps, which wvere thickened, fused, and ulcerated. haemorrhagic, friable vegetations were adherent to the ventricular aspect of the valve. the myocardium showed pale, irregular areas of softening. numerous systemic infarcts were also present, affecting kidneys, spleen, small intestine, and brain. histologically the aortic valve showed thrombus with an underlying inflammatory cell infiltrate and fibrosis. the myocardial lesions were typical bracht-wachter bodies, infarcts in various stages of healing, many showing active organisation and fibrosis consistent with weeks or months of duration. extensive embolisation from the valve was evident from the organising thrombi in the small arterial vessels of the heart and the multiple systemic infarcts. the kidneys showed a diffuse glomerulonephritis of membranoproliferative type. the findings indicated endocarditis of some months' duration superimposed on chronic valvular disease, presumably rheumatic in origin
Pharmacological Therapy: 3 g amoxycillin
Patient Outcome Assessment: despite intensive treatment he deteriorated over the next 24 hours and died

Family History: no family history of any kind of mitochondrial disease; none of the patient’s relatives contained the mutation in their blood mtdna
Medical\/Surgical History: at the age of 13 years, the patient experienced his first stroke-like episode with reversible aphasia, right hemiparesis and hemianopsia; exercise intolerance, progressive mental impairment and short stature had previously been noted; serum lactate was constantly raised
Signs and Symptoms: clinical symptoms and laboratory abnormalities typical of melas; devoid of any mutation in a gene previously associated with this disease; instead, the deletion of a single nucleotide (7630delt) within mt-co2, the gene of cytochrome c oxidase (cox) subunit ii (coii), was identified as the cause of his condition; this patient has previously been described in detail,8 and is thus only briefly summarised and updated here; at the age of 13 years, the patient experienced his first stroke-like episode with reversible aphasia, right hemiparesis and hemianopsia; exercise intolerance, progressive mental impairment and short stature had previously been noted; serum lactate was constantly raised; the patient developed secondarily generalised and myoclonic seizures, left ventricular hypertrophy, retinopathy and progressive nephropathy, and had recurrent headaches and vomiting; repeated mri of the brain over the years revealed an increasing number of focal lesions and progressive cortical atrophy throughout the cere- bral cortex, beginning and most pronounced in the left parieto-occipital lobe (fig 1); brain angiography showed no angiopathic alterations; basal ganglia calcifications were noted from the first neuroradiological examination (fig 1), and the most last mri scan taken showed moderate cerebellar lesions
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: repeated mri of the brain over the years revealed an increasing number of focal lesions and progressive cortical atrophy throughout the cerebral cortex, beginning and most pronounced in the left parieto-occipital lobe (fig 1); brain angiography showed no angiopathic alterations; basal ganglia calcifications were noted from the first neuro- radiological examination (fig 1), and the most last mri scan taken showed moderate cerebellar lesions; mtdna analyses: dna was isolated by standard procedures
Diagnosis: cytochrome-c oxidase deficiency
Laboratory Values: given the overt pathogenic role of 7630delt, we refrained from doing a single-fibre pcr-rflp correlation analysis, but instead used the scarce amount of biopsy material to analyse protein and mrna steady-state levels of various subunits of the respiratory chain to throw light on the pathogenic mechanism of 7630delt. as predicted, the protein levels of coii were dramatically reduced (fig 4a). however, levels of other subunits of respiratory complex iv were also diminished, although not all to the same extent. in stark contrast, (selected) subunits of the other four complexes of the respiratory chain, as well as a mitochondrial marker protein, voltage-dependent anion channel (vdac), were generally upregulated (fig 4b). expression of a nuclear protein (emerin) was comparable with controls
Pathology: a biopsy from the vastus lateralis muscle taken at 13 years of age was processed for routine histo- chemical staining. a small fibre bundle was fixed and processed for transmission electron microscopy. activities of respiratory chain enzymes and citrate synthase (cs) were measured in the homogenate of the frozen muscle; the muscle biopsy revealed pronounced, generalised cox hyporeactivity (.90% of muscle fibres) with numerous fibres completely non-reactive and only a few with near-normal reactivity (fig 2a,b). succinate dehydrogenase (sdh) staining showed the complementary pattern of mitochondrial prolifera- tion in muscle fibres (fig 2c). however, of the few arterioles identified in the muscle section, only one displayed pronounced sdh reactivity. the presence of ragged-red fibres (,2%) indicated subsarcolemmal as well as sarcoplasmic accumulation of mitochondria, which was also seen by transmission electron microscopy (fig 2d). like most muscle fibres of normal appearance, ragged-red fibres were hyporeactive or non-reactive for cox. mitochondrial proliferation was also reflected by the marked increase in cs activity in the muscle homogenate (table 1). assessment of respiratory chain enzymes corroborated the complex iv deficiency already denoted by histology; cox activity was barely detectable. other respiratory chain enzyme measurements independent from complex iv were either in the normal range or were also increased (table 1). southern blotting excluded large-scale rearrangements of muscle mtdna. as none of the previously reported melas mutations was found by the initial, partial sequence analysis,8 the entire muscle mtdna was finally sequenced. in total, 15 discrepancies from the revised cambridge reference sequence were found,12 14 of which were previously reported polymorph- isms16 17 (see supplementary materials for a complete listing). the 15th, a deletion of t at position 7630 (7630delt; fig 3a), however, is obviously pathogenic. this mutation, 7630delt, gives rise to a frameshift in the reading frame of mt-co2, resulting in a premature stop of translation (fig 3c). a peptide translated from mt-co2 harbouring 7630delt will thus consist of only 16 amino acids instead of 227. this mutation was not found in the two major collections of mtdna mutations.16 17 pcr-rflp analysis showed that 7630delt was in fact heteroplasmic in the patient’s muscle also (fig 3b). the deletion was also found in the patient’s blood, although at a much lower frequency
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient died at the age of 23 years; no postmortem examination was carried out

Medical\/Surgical History: diagnosed with chronic lymphocytic leukemia in 1973
Signs and Symptoms: 1973: diagnosis of chronic lymphocytic leukemia; 18 months later: congestive heart failure gradually developed; 3 months later: readmitted with incipient pulmonary edema; 2 months after starting tapazole: the patient's condition was somewhat improved although he was not hypothyroid and still had a hyperdynamic precordium with biventricular gallops; 8 months after tapazole: the patient was admitted because of ascites; over the next two months, his symptoms of congestive heart failure improved and mild exertion without symptoms was possible
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: 1973: physical examination (mild splenomegaly and several small axillary lymph nodes were noted); 18 months later after congestive heart failure: physical examination (mildly hypertensive (150/105 mmhg), tachycardic (100/regular), in moderate biventricular failure with a hyperdynamic precordium; the left ventricle was displaced (10 cm from the midsternal line), there was a soft apical systolic murmur, and biventricular atrial and ventricular gallops; the degree of splenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, and leukocytosis was unchanged); cardiac catheterization (showed a normal cardiac index and normal intracardiac pressures except for a left ventricular end diastolic pressure of 18 mmhg; there was no evidence of restrictive cardiomyopathy; global left ventricular hypokinesis with an ejection fraction of 36% was noted; complete obstruction of the left anterior descending coronary artery immediately distal to the first septal perforator was found; the remainder of the coronary circulation was normal); 4 months after tapazole: physical examination (heart rate had decreased to 80 beats/min and he was able to walk 150 feet without dyspnea); 8 months after tapazole: paracentesis (showed an exudative fluid without a bacterial or tuberculous process being confirmed); 2 months after resuming tapazole: physical examination (venous pressure became normal and precordial movements were less active; there was no change in his ascites and he was only mildly hypothyroid); radiography (heart size was normal); auscultation (gallops were no longer heard)
Diagnosis: congestive heart failure and endocardia1 fibroelastosis caused by chronic lymphocytic leukemia
Laboratory Values: 1973: peripheral white blood cell count was 75,000/mm3 with 87% mature lymphocytes and no blast forms. 4 months after tapazole treatment: serum t4 was now 1.6 ug/dl. 8 months after tapazole: the patient was now markedly hypothyroid. 5 months after starting radiotherapy, wbc count was 86,000/mm3 with 88% lymphocytes and he was markedly hypothyroid
Pathology: at autopsy, the heart weighed 530 g. the trabeculae carneae of the right ventricle appeared mildly thickened and there was focal subendocardial fibrosis. the right side of the heart displayed ventricular hypertrophy(5 mm in thickness) but the valves were delicate and without fibrosis. the endocardium was unremarkable. the entire endocardial surface of the left atrium and ventricle displayed a diffuse, pearly-white plaque which on cut sectioning measured 3-5 mm in thickness. the left ventricular wall was hypertrophied (19 mm in thickness). the mitral valve circumference was normal and its surface showed the pearly-white plaque. the chordae tendineae appeared to be thickened and shortened. post-mortem artery injection of radiopaque contrast medium showed a 95% stenosis of the mid-portion of the left anterior descending coronary artery; the remainder of the coronary circulation was widely patent. microscopic examination showed extensive endocardial fibrosis and elastosis. the elastic fibers were organized in multiple layers at the endomyocardial junction while in other areas they were totally disorganized and had a speckled appearance. clusters of mature lymphocytes similar to those seen in the bone marrow were found at the endomyocardial junction, and within the myocardium, the walls of the aorta, pulmonary arteries, and coronary vessels, the liver, spleen, lymph nodes, and the kidneys. a few bands of fibrous and elastic tissues were seen in the myocardium. there was no gross or histologic evidence of a myocardial infarction. there were atherosclerotic changes with mild lumenal stenosis throughout the coronary arterial tree except as noted in the left anterior descending vessel. the narrowing of this vessel was most likely caused by atherosclerosis. however, it is not known whether the leukemic infiltrate within and surrounding the vessel walls accelerated the atherosclerotic process. electron microscopic examination confirmed the presence of both elastic and collagen fibers in varying proportions in different areas. the myocardial cells were ultrastructurally reasonably well preserved without any significant pathologic changes. small areas fig. 5. photomicrograph showing endocardial fibroelastosis with elastic fibers (+) above the endocardium (voerhoeff’s elastic stain, x 150). of lymphocytic infiltration were seen throughout the myocardium. a large (50 cm x 20 cm) fibrotic fluid-filled cyst was found within the abdominal cavity compressing and partially obstructing both ureters. this finding represented the ascites which had been noted prior to death
Pharmacological Therapy: after diagnosis of myocarditis, treatment with digoxin and furosemide was begun. he underwent treatment with digitalis, diuretics, and nitroglycerin ointment, and strict bed rest for two weeks. when readmitted with incipient pulmonary edema, he was treated with increased amounts of diuretics, and hydralazine and prazosin were added to treat his congestive heart failure. treatment with tapazole was begun and the dosage gradually increased. 8 months later, tapazole was discontinued. tapazole was resumed (100 mg/day) after the trial of splenic irradiation. 5 months after radiation was started, tapazole and prazosin were discontinued
Interventional Therapy: a trial of splenic irradiation (300 rad) was given over three weeks after tapazole was discontinued; but this exacerbated the patient's congestive heart failure; later, an additional 100 rad of radiation was delivered to the spleen; then, 2 more courses of splenic irradiation were given
Patient Outcome Assessment: over the last month of his life (six months after beginning radiotherapy) he remained reasonably well and mild to moderate exertion was possible without dyspnea; although soft biventricular atrial and ventricular gallops were noted, there was no overt evidence of congestive heart failure; he was clinically euthyroid but the degree of ascites did not change; he received one more course of splenic irradiation (total cummulative dosage 450 rad) with a fall in the peripheral wbc count to 17,000/mm3; he died suddenly while at home
Short Diagnosis: congestive heart failure; endocardial fibroelastosis; chronic lymphocytic leukemia

Family History: this 3 1/2-year-old boy was born to nonconsanguineous parents from the state of chihuahua in mexico, after an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery; a brother had died with a liver problem after an unexplained coma occurring at three months of age; the parents and three older siblings are well
Medical\/Surgical History: at three months of age the patient was admitted in coma to the emergency room of a community hospital, where had a cardiac arrest; his blood sugar was 15 mg per deciliter (0.83 mmol per liter); hepatomegaly and cardiomegaly were noticed for the first time; hepatomegaly resolved with appropriate and intensive care, and the patient recovered; at six months of age was brought to the university of california, los angeles, medical center in congestive heart failure after an episode of upper respiratory tract infection; hepatomegaly and hypotonia were observed; on day 3, he became lethargic; generalized seizure activity and cardiac arrest developed, but was successfully revived; laboratory studies revealed a blood sugar of 15 mg per deciliter (0.83 mmol per liter) without associated acidosis or ketosis; mild elevation of serum aspartate aminotransferase (sgot) (337 iu per liter; normal, 6 to 36) and alanine aminotransferase (sgpt) (179 iu per liter; normal, 10 to 45); and hyperammonemia (300 jug per deciliter [177 iimol per liter] ; normal, <69); delayed milestones (developmental quotient 66), proximal muscle weakness, and growth retardation (weight and height below the third percentile) were noted after recovery; cardiac catheterization showed a minimal atrialseptal defect and bilateral ventricular hypertrophy; metabolic studies showed normal glucose, galactose, and fructose tolerance and a normal 10-hour fasting blood sugar, with no increase in lactate, pyruvate, or ketone bodies; cortisol and insulin studies, the blood sugar response to glucagon stimulation, and urine amino acid and organic acid chromatography also gave normal results; the electroencephalogram, brain scan, and chromosomal studies were unremarkable; blood sugar and ammonia, sgot, sgpt, and creatine phosphokinase were all normal between acute episodes; also normal were the levels of electrolytes, calcium phosphorus, magnesium, bilirubin, thyroxine, thyroid stimulating hormone, and growth hormone; results of total protein and electrophoresis, cerebrospinal fluid studies, and studies of immune function were also normal; the patient presented again with cardiorespiratory arrest after upper respiratory tract infections at the ages of 20 months, two years, and 33 months; he recovered slowly each time; the episodes were associated with liver enlargement, elevation of the transaminases to 2000 or more iu per liter, and elevation of creatine phosphokinase to 1500 to 33,000 iu per liter; maintenance glucose requirements varied from normal (3 mg per kilogram of body weight per minute) to slightly elevated (5 to 7 mg per kilogram per minute); during the 11th admission, the diagnosis of carnitine deficiency was considered because of the fatty changes in the liver and the lack of production of ketone bodies after 24 hours of fasting; the deficiency was confirmed by carnitine measurement in serum, muscle, and liver samples; at that time the patient had a normal height, weight, and head circumference, a developmental quotient of 40, and a variety of neuromuscular abnormalities; a cat scan of his brain revealed marked enlargement of both lateral ventricles and of the sulci between the cerebral gyri; carnitine studies and therapy were instituted

Laboratory Values: the platelet count was 9000 per cubic millimeter; the prothrombin time was prolonged, and hyperglycemia was present; the platelet count rose to the range of 20,000 to 30,000 per cubic millimeter after a platelet transfusion; four blood cultures yielded group b streptococci, which were sensitive to cefoxitin; the hematocrit was 30.1 percent. the glucose level was 374 mg per deciliter (20.7 mmol per liter); the lactate dehydrogenase level was 919 u per liter, and the creatine kinase level was normal. a specimen of arterial blood, drawn while the patient was breathing 2 liters of oxygen per minute, showed that the partial pressure of oxygen was 80 mm hg, the partial pressure of carbon dioxide was 44 mm hg, and the ph was 7.42. the urine was normal, except that the sediment contained 5 to 10 hyaline casts per low-power field, with 3 to 5 red cells and 0 to 2 white cells per high-power field. the values for total protein, calcium, phosphorus, bilirubin, creatine kinase, and amylase were normal; a specimen of arterial blood, drawn while the patient was breathing an enriched oxygen mixture, showed that the partial pressure of oxygen was 327 mm hg, the partial pressure of carbon dioxide was 56 mm hg, and the ph was 7.47

Short Diagnosis: Congestive heart failure; aneurysm of the left sinus of Valsalva with rupture into the pulmonary artery; bicuspid aortic valve, with calcification and stenosis; aortic insufficiency; atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular rate; subacute infective endocarditis, streptococcus group b; obesity; non-insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus

Family History: the patient had no personal or family history of hypertension, diabetes mellitus or coronary heart disease
Medical\/Surgical History: a 60-year-old woman was admitted to our department on 11 april 2016 with complaints of intermittent abdominal distension for the past 3 years which aggravated 6 months earlier; the abdominal distension would be triggered by cold or hot diet, but was not accompanied by abdominal pain, vomiting, hematochezia, or diarrhea; a colonoscopy 3 years ago showed multiple, small ulcers in the ascending colon, leading to a diagnosis of ulcerative colitis (uc) and subsequent treatment with mesalazine for 6 months; her symptoms persisted and a repeat colonoscopy revealed that the ulcers were still present; the patient took herbal decoctions occasionally; a detailed history revealed that in her 30s, the patient had recurrent painful aphthous ulcers almost once a month; she also had a 10-year history of anemia, a 6- year of asthma and recurrent conjunctival congestion in her left eye for 1 year; two months before admission, she began experiencing chest pains with increasing frequency; the patient had no personal or family history of hypertension, diabetes mellitus or coronary heart disease
Signs and Symptoms: on admission, her physical examination revealed a blood pressure of 160/90 mm hg and conjunctival congestion in the left eye.
Comorbidities: ulcers; anemia; asthma; conjunctival congestion; chest pains
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: during her stay, colonoscopy was not recommended because of her frequent chest pains, while an ekg showed a st-t segment depression in a vl, v4, v5, and v6; ultrasound cardiogram (ucg) showed an enlarged left ventricle with widened ascending aorta and moderate aortic insufficiency; coronary artery ct revealed a slight calcification with calcium score 12.5 and mild stenosis of her left coronary artery (lca) and left anterior descending branch (lad); ophthalmic consultation showed retina vasculitis in her left eye; an expansion in the thoracic and abdominal aorta was revealed by an abdominal computed tomography (ct); a computed tomography angiography (cta) on may 3, 2016 showed a 17.5 21.3 mm-diameter aneurysm in the left subclavian artery (fig; 1a), a 34.3 mm-diameter aneurysm in the descending aorta (fig; 1b) and a 34.8 mm-diameter aneurysm in the proximal abdominal aorta (fig; 1c); taking the history of recurrent aphthous ulcers, ulcers in the ascending colon, and the cta results into consideration, she was diagnosed with bd according to international criteria for behcet’s disease (icbd) (table 1); the patient’s activity index score was 3 according to the behcet’s disease current activity form (bdcaf); firstly, uc patients always present with abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, while our patient did not exhibit these symptoms and her occult blood test was negative; secondly, the patient was treated with mesalazine for 6 months when she was first diagnosed with uc, but her symptoms showed no improvement and a repeat colonoscopy showed the ulcers still existed as before; however, after treatment with methylprednis- olone combined with cyclophosphamide for 3 months, the colon ulcers resolved; the patient we reported had a recurrent and relapsing conjunctival congestion for about 1 year and at last was diagnosed with retina vasculitis; in our case, we used crp, esr combined with bdcaf scores to evaluate the activity of the disease, and our results showed the bdcaf score index was closely correlated with the level of esr and crp; the case we report carried hla-b13/40 phenotype which has hitherto not been widely recognized
Diagnosis: behcet's disease
Laboratory Values: laboratory analysis revealed that her hemoglobin was 8.5g/l, c-reactive protein (crp) and erythrocyte sedimentation rate (esr) were elevated at 75.8 mg/l and 102 mm/h, respectively. stool routine and occult blood test were negative; further immunologic test revealed positive for antinuclear antibodies (ana) and anticentromere antibodies (aca)1:1000 (using indirect immunofluorescence assay), but negative for antibodies to proteinase-3(pr3-anca), antibodies to myeloper- oxidase(mpo-anca), anticardiolipin antibodies, anti-b2gp1 antibodies, tb test, and ppd (diameter of the nodule is 2mm). gene testing was positive for hla-b13:02 and hla-b 40:01 phenotypes
Pathology: bone marrow biopsy showed no pathologic change that could accounted for her anemia
Pharmacological Therapy: she was then treated with methylprednisolone 32 mg daily combined with cyclophosphamide 50 mg twice a day orally starting on june 8, 2016. however, the patient had difficulty falling asleep after taking the medicine. so methylpred- nisolone was replaced with prednisolone 40mg daily after a week. after 2 months, her abdominal distension was relieved and the chest pains less frequent, leading to a reduction in cyclophosphamide to 50mg once a day starting on august 2, 2016
Interventional Therapy: immunosuppressive agents/therapeutic use
Patient Outcome Assessment: three months later after she was first treated, her activity index score reduced from 3 to 1, crp and esr levels declined to 18 mm/h and 10 mg/l, respectively; the colonoscopy found no ulcers in the colon; cta was repeated and showed an 18.6 mm- diameter aneurysm in the left subclavian artery and a 31.6mm- diameter aneurysm in the descending aorta, and a 34.1mm-diameter aneurysm in the proximal abdominal aorta

Patient Outcome Assessment: upon examination the following month, the patient was asymptomatic with an ef of 40–45%; she currently continues to be completely free of symptoms 1 year following the event

Medical\/Surgical History: she was diagnosed with dilated cardiomyopathy in 1997
Signs and Symptoms: she was admitted to a local hospital after being diagnosed with heart failure nyha class iii with acute pulmonary edema; she reported an almost immediate improvement in symptoms after the implant, with much better exercise tolerance; six minute walk distance increased from 293 meters prior to implant to 366 meters by 6 months post implant; she did well until april 2002, when she suddenly noted pulsations in her abdomen; she presented to the pacemaker clinic, where diaphragmatic contractions were observed and confirmed to be due to pacemaker stimulation; before her operation, she reported feeling quite well, with no change in symptoms since the device was reprogrammed; in june 2002, she reported feeling recurrent dyspnea on exertion and fatigue consistent with her previous heart failure symptoms
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: cardiac catheterization (revealed normal coronary arteries and severe left ventricular dysfunction); after acute pulmonary edema: electrocardiogram (revealed sinus rhythm and left bundle branch block (lbbb) with qrs width of 150 msec); echocardiogram (revealed moderate mitral regurgitation and left ventricular end-diastolic diameter (lvedd) of 7.1 cm; left ventricular ejection fraction (lvef) was estimated to be 20%); ensuing months: serial electrocardiogram (demonstrated lbbb at a range of heart rates (50 to 130 bpm)); may 2001: metabolic stress test (revealed maximal o2 consumption to be 13 ml/kg/min); echocardiogram (showed findings identical to the previous one); postoperatively: echocardiogram (showed mild mitral regurgitation, lvef of 35%, with lvedd decreasing to 5 cm); april 2002: chest x-ray (revealed dislodgement of the left ventricular lead, which had migrated back to the superior vena cava and was stimulating the phrenic nerve; the device was reprogrammed to vvi mode at a lower rate of 40 bpm in order to avoid pacing); preoperative electrocardiogram (revealed a narrow intrinsic qrs complex of 100 msec); follow up electrocardiograms (continued to demonstrate a narrow qrs complex at a range of heart rates (60 to 110 bpm)); june 2002: electrocardiogram (at this time revealed recurrent lbbb with a qrs width of 150 msec)
Diagnosis: she developed progressive heart failure reaching new york heart association class iii by june of 2000. after biventricular pacing therapy for heart failure, she presented with loss of left bundle branch block
Pharmacological Therapy: she was managed medically before developing progressive heart failure. her medications included digoxin, furosemide, lisinopril, carvedilol, aspirin, and atorvastatin. medications and dosages were unchanged from those pre-implant
Interventional Therapy: in october 2001, she was approved for the medtronic insync r iii biventricular pacing protocol; later that month, she had the device implanted without complication; the left ventricular lead was placed in a postero-lateral branch of the coronary sinus; the electrocardiogram during biventricular pacing revealed a narrower qrs pattern, with qrs width of 110 msec; when she presented with symptoms indicating the the left ventricular lead was out of position, surgery was initially indicated to reposition the lead and then surgery was cancelled as her symptoms improved; the device was left in vvi mode; in june 2002, the patient was brought back to the operating room for attempted repositioning of the left ventricular lead; however, her left subclavian vein was found to be occluded, so that a guiding sheath could not be inserted; the left ventricular lead was removed; a venogram and subsequent doppler study revealed the right subclavian vein to have a high grade stenosis as well, likely congenital in origin; in july of 2002, the patient had an epicardial lead placed on the lateral left ventricle via thoracoscopy, and biventricular pacing resumed
Patient Outcome Assessment: her symptoms have once again improved; repeat echocardiogram in august of 2002 continued to show lvef of 35%, lvedd of 5 cm, and mild mitral regurgitation; she has been followed for 2 months thus far, and on routine evaluations of her pacemaker, she continues to have underlying lbbb with qrs width 150 msec on her intrinsic electrocardiogram

Family History: the patient's husband had an out-of-hospital cardiac arrest earlier that day and was brought to our emergency room and subsequently admitted to the coronary care unit; he had recurrent ventricular fibrillation and could not be successfully resuscitated
Medical\/Surgical History: the patient's medical history included hypertension and hypothyroidism; she denied having had a similar episode of pain; had regular appointments with her primary care physician; her medication included oral furosemide 20 mg and levothyroxine 100 µg, both once daily; she denied allergies
Signs and Symptoms: she presented to our emergency room 30 min after her husband expired with 8/10, substernal chest pain with concurrent diaphoresis and dyspnoea
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: physical examination (on presentation, the patient was afebrile, with a blood pressure of 105/55, heart rate of 93 bpm, respiratory rate of 20/min and an oxygen saturation of 98% on room air; on physical examination, she was in significant distress due to pain; her skin was warm and moist, with minimal crackles in bilateral bases, regular rate and rhythm, 2/6 systolic murmur of the apex without radiation, no rubs, elevated jugular vein distention of 8 cm, strong peripheral pulses and no peripheral oedema; the abdomen was soft, non-tender, non-distended, with bowel sounds, and the patient was alert and oriented without focal neurological deficits.); ecg (revealed normal sinus rhythm with 2–3 mm st segment elevations in leads v2–v3 and q waves in leads v1–v3, suggestive of anterior wall infarct); echocardiogram (revealed left ventricular ejection fraction of 30–35% with mild concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, akinesis of the apex and 2/3 of the inferoseptum and apical inferior-anterior wall segments, suggesting ischaemic damage at the left anterior descending artery distribution versus takotsubo cardiomyopathy); angiogram (showed non-obstructive coronary artery disease with luminal irregularities; the left ventriculography showed an ejection fraction of 35% with akinesis of apical wall and hyperkinesis of basal segments.)
Diagnosis: takotsubo cardiomyopathy
Laboratory Values: the complete blood count, basic metabolic panel and coagulation tests were within normal limits. the cardiac enzymes were increased with a troponin i of 2.59 ng/ml (normal range 0.015–0.045 ng/ml), creatine phosphokinase of 84 u/l (normal range 26–192 u/l)
Pharmacological Therapy: the patient received aspirin 162 mg and prasugrel 60 mg
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient remained haemodynamically stable and was started on oral heart failure medications, including lisinopril 2.5 mg daily and metoprolol tartrate 12.5 mg two times a day; her pain and shortness of breath resolved and she was discharged home after 48 h of hospitalisation in stable condition; a repeat echocardiogram 2 months later showed resolution of her cardiomyopathy and an ejection fraction of 65–70%, with normal left ventricular motion

Medical\/Surgical History: poor hearing in the left ear was noticed following a head injury three years before this presentation; otherwise had recently been well, was on no medication and did not smoke; her left calf was wasted due to childhood poliomyelitis
Signs and Symptoms: she suddenly developed slurred speech, diplopia, paraesthesiae on the left side of the face, and weakness of the left arm; she had vomited initially and developed a left sided headache later; two years later, she was again referred, after suffering a major dominant hemisphere stroke, with dysphasia, facial weakness and a dense right hemiplegia
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: examination (revealed acromegalic facies and hands; there were splinter haemorrhages in the fingers; she was normotensive and in sinus rhythm); neurological examination (revealed nerve deafness in the left ear, and mild left finger-nose ataxia; power was reduced int eh left leg, and the left calf was wasted following childhood poliomyelitis); plain and computed tomography (showed a large left acoustic neuroma complicated by hydrocephalus, and enlargement of the pituitary fossa); 2 years later: electrocardiograph (within normal limits); computed tomography (showed a left hemisphere infarct); angiography (showed complete occlusion of the left internal carotid artery) echocardiography (demonstrated a large left atrial myxoma)
Diagnosis: acoustic neuroma and hydrocephalus and stroke due to axial myxoma
Interventional Therapy: after discovering the large left acoustic neuroma, surgery was decided; following a decompressive shunt the acoustic neuroma was removed, and transethmoidal hypophysectomy was performed for a chromophobe adenoma during a later admission; two years later, th elarge left atrial myxoma was removed under cardiopulmonary bypass
Patient Outcome Assessment: since her cardiopulmonary bypass surgery, she has been making a slow but encouraging recovery from her stoke

Medical\/Surgical History: colon resection for villous adenoma 1.5 years ago; right total hip replacement for degenerative joint disease 1 year ago; essential hypertension had been controlled for several years with medical therapy
Signs and Symptoms: low back pain that had appeared and progressed in severity during the preceding 6 weeks.physical exam revealed the patient to be afebrile and neurologically intact; the only positive finding was a soft, blowing, grade ii/vi systolic murmur over the cardiac apex that had not been described previously; over the next several days, the patient became febrile
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: lumbosacral spinal x-rays revealed disk space narrowing and end plate destruction at the l2~3 level; a radionuclide bone scan demonstrated increased uptake at l2 and l3 with no other lesions; needle biopsy of the l2-3disk space was performed; echocardiogram revealed both aortic and mitral valve vegetations
Diagnosis: hypertension, congestive heart failure, respiratory failure; native valve endocarditis, vertebral osteomyelitis
Laboratory Values: hematocrit was 31.3%, and leukocyte count was 9,400/ram 3 with a normal dif-ferential. blood cultures drawn over a 2-day period yielded coagulase-nega-tive staphylococci in five of six sets. both isolates from the disk space and blood were identified as s. warneri. disk susceptibility studies revealed resistance to penicillin, while the isolates were susceptible to oxacillin and cephalothin. mic and mbc tests performed by broth dilution methods (nccls, 1985) revealed vancomycin i and 2 ~g/ml, nafcillin 0.5 and 1 ~g/ml, and rifampin less than 0.1 and less than 0.1 ~g/ml, respectively
Pathology: needle biopsy of the l2-3disk space: pathology was negative for malignancy, and a gram stain showed a moderate number of neutrophils but no bacteria
Pharmacological Therapy: 4 weeks of vancomycin and gentamicin therapy followed by 2 weeks of vancomycin and rifampin therapy. dicloxacillin and rifampin
Interventional Therapy: surgical replacement of destroyed aortic and mitral valves and debridement of an aortic valve ring abscess
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient has now been followed for over 4 years and remains free of infec-tion
Short Diagnosis: hypertension; congestive heart failure; respiratory failure; native valve endocarditis; vertebral osteomyelitis

Medical\/Surgical History: has recurrent breast cancer and anthracycline-induced cardiac failure; was perimenopausal and had no comorbidities including diabetes mellitus, hypertension, or any history of underlying cardiac problems

Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: march 1999: cxr, abdominal ultrasound, and bone scan (showed no evidence of metastasis); ecg (normal); 30 months later: cxr, abdominal uss, and bone scan (no evidence of distant metastases); march 2002: echo (demonstrated global ventricular dysfunction with lvef of 42%); ecg (normal); april 2002: echo (showed persistent lvef of 42%); 6 months later: echo (demonstrated moderate left ventricular dysfunction); june 2003: echo (demonstrated stable left ventricular function); october 2004: echo (improved lvef of 55%); march 2007: echo (revealed asymptomatic deterioration in lvef to 38.3% and treatment was discontinued); november 2007: echo (lvef has recovered to 47%)
Diagnosis: cardiac failure due to anthracycline chemotherapy
Laboratory Values: 30 months later: ca 15-3 was not elevated. march 2002: normal cardiac enzymes
Pathology: march 1999: staining was positive for oestrogen and negative for progesterone receptor. 30 months later: fine needle aspiratory cytology confirmed breast cancer recurrence of clavicular mass. immunohistochemistry for her2/neu status was strongly positive (3+) on the mastectomy sample

Interventional Therapy: march 1999: patient underwent mastectomy and axillary node clearance for a grade 3, pt1 pn3 ductal carcinoma of the left breast
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient received trastuzumab for a total of 46 months to a cumulative dose of 146 mg/kg (total dose 9815 mg); she remains disease free with no radiological evidence of recurrence on a recent ct scan and asymptomatic of cardiac dysfunction more than 6 years after recurrence of breast cancer

Medical\/Surgical History: he was previously healthy; further inquiry revealed that was treated for leptospirosis during a febrile illness in the past
Signs and Symptoms: he presented to the medical casualty ward with fever, arthralgia, and myalgia for one day; he complained of mild dysuria but had normal urine output; he did not have chest pain or shortness of breath; on the second day of illness, he developed hypotension with tachycardia and dyspnoea; on the third day of illness, he developed rapid atrial fibrillation
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: physical examination (on examination, patient was afebrile, anicteric; his blood pressure was 90/60 mmhg and pulse rate 76 bpm; rest of the examination was unremarkable); second day of illness: ecg (ecg revealed sinus tachycardia with st depression in leads v4 – v6); chest x-ray (showed gross cardiomegaly and bilateral pulmonary shadows); physical examination (cvp (central venous pressure) was 16 cmh2o); 2d echocardiogram (revealed dilatation of all four chambers, severe global hypokinesia and ejection fraction of 20%.)

Laboratory Values: initial investigations performed on the day of admission revealed neutrophil leukocytosis, mild thrombocytopaenia and microscopic haematuria. renal function and liver enzymes were within normal limits. urine analysis revealed pus cells 05 – 06 /hpf, red cells 30 – 35 /hpf. crp (c-reactive protein) was 75 mg/dl. on the third day of illness, platelet count dropped to 10 × 103 ?/l and he was given platelet transfusions to prevent bleeding. his serum creatinine increased to 362 ? mol/l by the 5th day of illness and alt (alanine transaminase) and ast (aspartate transaminase) were markedly elevated up to 2726 u/l and 7438 u/l respectively. dengue and mycoplasma infections were excluded. blood cultures were negative. leptospira igm antibody performed on the 5th day of illness was positive (igg negative)
Pharmacological Therapy: a clinical diagnosis of leptospirosis was made and he was started on intravenous penicillin in addition to adequate hydration. on the second day, troponin i was 12.77 ng/ml (normal range < 0.40). after being diagnosed with myocarditis, he was transferred to icu (intensive care unit) as he needed inotropic support. intravenous antibiotics including penicillin, meropenem and levofloxacin were continued. on the third day of illness, he developed rapid atrial fibrillation, unresponsive to digoxin and intravenous amiodarone. we started intravenous methylprednisolone
Interventional Therapy: he was electively ventilated on the 3rd day of illness due to severe respiratory distress
Patient Outcome Assessment: patient developed refractory shock and died of persistent ventricular tachycardia despite optimal treatment in the icu

Family History: parents are cousins; both parents were of normal height and neither showed any minor anomalies of the evc syndrome spectrum; the patient had two healthy sisters; his parents were heterozygous carriers of the nonsense mutation he had
Medical\/Surgical History: in 1998, the patient underwent successful ostium primum atrial septal defect closure through a midsternotomy; he re-presented with embolic cerebral ictus in 2007, and cavotricuspid isthmus ablation for common atrial flutter was performed successfully; there were no serious aftereffects
Signs and Symptoms: high-pitched systolic murmur discovered during routine examination
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: physical examination (his morphological features were: normal mouth opening with missing lower incisors; small chest, as determined by a cardiothoracic examination; and disproportionately short extremities with one additional postaxial digit on each hand; no sensory-motor deficit was noted; the patient presented with mild mental retardation.); genetic analysis in early infancy (showed a previously reported homozygous nonsense mutation); electrocardiography (showed sinus rhythm with hemiblock and right bundle branch block); echocardiography (revealed a dilated and hypertrophic left ventricle; these abnormalities produced a flow that was directed tot he left atrial appendage, leading to severe mitral valve regurgitation; the patient's systolic pulmonary artery pressure was 50 mmhg and his aortic valve was normal)
Diagnosis: mitral valve regurgitation associated with ellis-van creveld syndrome
Pharmacological Therapy: ramipril, duloxetine, alprazolam, acenocumarol
Interventional Therapy: the patient was scheduled for mitral valve surgery; in the operating theatre, the patient’s right femoral artery was cannulated; a right thoracotomy was performed on the fourth intercostal space and bicaval cannulation was established; both veins were excluded; the operation used a normothermic cardiopulmonary bypass without cross-clamping of the aorta in the beating heart; to avoid air embolisms, continuous carbon dioxide (co2) field flooding was applied using a carbonaid co2 diffuser (cardia innovation ab, stockholm, sweden); the attempt to perform a mitral valve repair was unsuccessful and a bileaflet mechanical valve (no; 29) was implanted; no complications associated with anaesthesia occurred
Patient Outcome Assessment: the patient’s postoperative recovery was uneventful and he was discharged on postoperative day 10; after two years of follow-up, echocardiography revealed optimal function of the mitral valve and a decrease in systolic pulmonary artery pressure (30 mmhg)
Short Diagnosis: mitral valve regurgitation; ellis-van creveld syndrome

extensive anterior and inferior-wall areas that were electrically inactive; and st-segment elevation from v1 to v6 and in i avl, with positive t waves from v1 to v6; the chest x-ray (05; 10; 2008) showed cardiomegaly at the expense of the left ventricle (lv); there was slight pericardial effusion; the pulmonary artery pressure was estimated at 30 mmhg; the coronary angiography (may 14, 2008) identified occlusion of the anterior interventricular branch of the left coronary artery, a 90% lesion at the emergence of the first diagonal branch and a 70% in the left marginal branch; the electrocardiogram (may 24, 2008) showed sinus rhythm; hr of 75 bpm; pr interval of 200 ms; qrs duration of 80 ms; low qrs voltage in the frontal plane; extensive electrically inactive anterior area and st-segment elevation from v1 to v6 and i and avl, with positive t waves in the same leads; a mid-apical aneurysm was identified in the left ventricle; the pulmonary artery pressure was estimated at 67 mmhg
Diagnosis: myocardial infarction; ventricular aneurysm; heart failure; ventricular fibrillation
Laboratory Values: the laboratory assessment (may 10, 2008) showed glycemia of 94 mg/dl; urea of 43 mg/dl; creatinine of 1.07 mg/dl; sodium of 137 meq/l; potassium of 4.5 meq/l; hemoglobin of 12.6 g/dl; leukocytes at 6,500/mm3; platelets at 286,000/m3; inr of 1.1; aptt (patient/control ratio) of 1.12; ckmb of 6.46 ng/ml and troponin of 6.27 ng/ml; the markers of myocardial necrosis were normal
Pathology: at the necropsy, the aorta presented moderate to intense atheromatosis, with marked calcification of its abdominal section. the heart presented a globus shape, at the expense of the lv anterior region (figure 4). cross-sections of the lv showed intense aneurysmatic dilatation in the lv cavity, the result of a previous extensive transmural myocardial infarction in the septal, anteroseptal, anterior and anterolateral walls, from the basis to the apex, with extensive mural thrombosis, as well as in the inferior wall, from the middle to the apex, with the involvement of approximately 60% of the ventricular muscle (figure 5). in spite of the presence of cavitary thrombi, no systemic thromboembolism was detected. the histological analysis showed that extensive areas of myocardial tissue had been replaced by fibrosis. the pericardium presented fibrosis, with the parietal and visceral leaflets fastened firmly to each other in the anterior projection of ventricular aneurysm. there were signs of congestive hf represented by hydrothorax to the right and hydroperitoneum, with approximately 360 ml and 480 ml of citrine-yellow fluid, respectively. the dissection and histological analysis of the epicardial coronaries demonstrated severe obstructive atherosclerotic coronary lesions (figure 6)

Short Diagnosis: myocardial infarction; ventricular aneurysm; heart failure; ventricular fibrillation

Short Diagnosis: torsades de pointes; nonsustained ventricular tachycardia; nonamyloidotic light chain cardiomyopathy; monoclonal gammopathies; nephrotic syndrome

Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: physical examination (the patient was an ill-looking, pale, and thin woman, clutching her abdomen; the blood pressure was 120/80 mmhg and the pulse 102/min; the respiratory rate and body temperature were normal; auscultation of the heart revealed a left parastemal systolic murmur grade 2/6; the abdomen was diffusely tender on palpation, without evidence of ascites or organomegaly.); neurological examination (revealed a mild decrease of both muscle strength and sensation in the legs and reduced patellar and achilles reflexes); chest and abdominal radiographs and computerized tomography, transvaginal ultrasonography, gastroscopy and contrast studies of the small and large bowel were unremarkable; repeat physicale xaminaiton (the temperature rose to 38'c, the abdominal pain worsened, and a left foot drop evolved; purpura appeared on both legs, the lower abdomen and buttocks); electrocardiogram (showed non-specific t wave changes); chest x-ray (exhibited pulmonary congestion); echocardiogram (displayed a hypokinetic left ventricle with severely decreased ejection fraction of 25% and fractional shortening of 15%); 5 weeks after admission when generalized convulsions repeated: brain ct and csf examinations (normal)

Patient Outcome Assessment: during continued medication with prednisone 1 mg/kg body weight/day and weekly intravenous cyclophosphamide 500 mg, the patient slowly recovered; a repeat echocardiogram showed improvement of left ventricular contractility and ejection fraction; after two months of hospitalization, she was discharged with a regimen of daily prednisone 0.5 mg/kg body weight and monthly intravenous pulse cyclophosphamide 500 mg; on follow-up five months after discharge, there were neither abdominal pains, purpura, nor signs of heart failure, but the left foot drop was still present; the serum complement levels were within the normal range; the echocardiogram showed a near-normal ejection fraction (ejection fraction 47% and fractional shortening 30%)

Medical\/Surgical History: after an uneventful pregnancy, the child was born at term without complications
Signs and Symptoms: at the age of 4 weeks, the girl presented with generalized muscular hypotonia and tachydyspnea; the further clinical course was complicated by persistent severe neutropenia
Diagnostic Techniques and Procedures: echocardiography; skeletal muscle biopsy; bone marrow histopathology
Diagnosis: cytochrome c oxidase (cox) enzyme deficiency; fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy
Laboratory Values: extensive metabolic screening of serum, urine and liquor including repeated determination of lactate levels at this time was normal
Pathology: subsequent analysis of mitochondrial respiratory chain enzyme activity from a skeletal muscle biopsy showed a significantly decreased cox activity and supported the suspected diagnosis of fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy due to sco2 deficiency; direct sequencing of the entire coding regions and flanking intron boundaries of the sco2 gene revealed two heterozygous single base pair mutations in exon 1. the first mutation was a change of guanine to adenine at position 1541 (1541g>a) leading to an amino acid substitution (e140k). this mutation has been identified previously in all patients with sco2 deficiency either in the homozygote or compound heterozygote state, and is therefore called ‘common mutation’. the second mutation changed thymine 1602 to guanine (1602t>g), leading to a yet unknown amino acid exchange (v160g). the mutation is located in a conserved region of the sco2 gene, although this particular amino acid residue has changed during phylogeny (isoleucine in yeast vs. valine in human). sco2 gene analysis of the parents showed inheritance with the heterozygote 1541g>a mutation in the mother and the 1602t>g mutation in the father. neither the 1541g>a nor the 1602t>g mutation was detected in 100 healthy control individuals; bone marrow histopathology revealed defective maturation of myeloid progenitor cells (promyelocyte arrest) similar to the findings in inherited infantile agranulocytosis (kostmann syndrome)
Patient Outcome Assessment: consecutively, the patient developed progressive neurological symptoms including uncontrolable seizures and finally died of septic shock in neutropenia due to serratia marcescens sepsis at the age of 4 months
Short Diagnosis: fatal infantile cardioencephalomyopathy; cytochrome c oxidase (cox) enzyme deficiency
